WEBVTT

00:01.083 --> 00:07.792
♪

00:07.792 --> 00:10.125
(stomping)

00:10.125 --> 00:11.083
Oh,<i> Cannonball Run?</i>

00:11.083 --> 00:12.625
COLLEEN: Ugh, Run-DMC?

00:12.625 --> 00:16.583
<i>Born to Run, </i>uh,<i> Clueless?</i>

00:16.583 --> 00:18.291
<i>The Running Man!</i>

00:18.291 --> 00:19.750
-All right, now, come on.
-Oh.

00:19.750 --> 00:21.458
I'm running, I'm a man, what?

00:21.458 --> 00:23.166
Well, we all got
the running part.

00:23.166 --> 00:25.000
Oh, I am outta shape.

00:25.000 --> 00:26.583
I need to start workin' out

00:26.583 --> 00:28.542
'cause I'm livin' for
someone else now, you know.

00:28.542 --> 00:30.625
-Not you, for Lark.
-Oh, thank you.

00:30.625 --> 00:32.458
GREG: I mean, I wanna be able
to do that<i> Dirty Dancing </i>lift

00:32.458 --> 00:34.291
at her wedding, you know?

00:34.291 --> 00:36.000
Do that.

00:36.000 --> 00:37.208
One of those?

00:37.208 --> 00:38.333
It'd be beautiful, right?

00:38.333 --> 00:40.125
I feel like that
would be maybe weird.

00:40.125 --> 00:42.667
You know, I think
you should join my gym.

00:42.667 --> 00:44.083
They helped me lose 60 pounds.

00:44.083 --> 00:45.417
Yeah, wait, what?

00:45.417 --> 00:47.083
Oh.

00:47.083 --> 00:48.500
Mm-hmm.

00:48.500 --> 00:51.709
♪

00:51.709 --> 00:53.750
CLINTON: Hey, you must be Greg!

00:53.750 --> 00:56.000
Good morning, Greg!

00:56.000 --> 00:57.542
Clinton Chestnut, CPT.

00:57.542 --> 01:00.542
Oh, Greg Short, DAD.

01:00.542 --> 01:01.625
New dad.

01:01.625 --> 01:03.458
Ah, yeah, I see that.

01:03.458 --> 01:05.333
(chuckling)

01:05.333 --> 01:08.125
Hey, every great journey
starts with a single step.

01:08.125 --> 01:10.375
Are you ready to
take that step, Greg?

01:10.375 --> 01:12.750
Yeah, I think so, is it far?

01:12.750 --> 01:14.083
We've already begun.

01:14.083 --> 01:16.125
-Come on, I'll show ya around.
-Okay!

01:16.125 --> 01:19.208
CLINTON: Let's do this,
come on.

01:19.208 --> 01:20.792
With our state-of-the-art
technology,

01:20.792 --> 01:24.375
you can row any boat
through any time period.

01:24.375 --> 01:26.542
Stanley here is on the<i> Amistad.</i>

01:26.542 --> 01:29.125
Dawn is on one of
the lifeboats from the<i> Titanic. </i>

01:29.125 --> 01:30.917
-Oh, whoa.
-Uh,

01:30.917 --> 01:32.709
women and children only, Greg.

01:32.709 --> 01:33.709
Know what I mean?

01:33.709 --> 01:35.083
Come on.

01:35.083 --> 01:37.875
CLINTON: Now, I have been
in a lot of locker rooms, Greg,

01:37.875 --> 01:39.834
but these towels are the best.

01:39.834 --> 01:43.083
Thread count so high
they stopped countin'.

01:43.083 --> 01:44.166
You like to dance, Greg?

01:44.166 --> 01:46.500
GREG: Yeah, I did a little
soft shoe tap in my day.

01:46.500 --> 01:49.166
Yeah, my mom let me
chase my dream.

01:49.166 --> 01:50.792
Soft shoe tap is cool,

01:50.792 --> 01:52.959
but square dancing's
more of a high-octane,

01:52.959 --> 01:54.625
whole body experience.

01:54.625 --> 01:56.291
-Yeah.
INSTRUCTOR: Now, two by two,

01:56.291 --> 01:59.208
let's promenade,
promenade, promenade.

01:59.208 --> 02:03.458
Now squat, squat, squat, squat!

02:03.458 --> 02:06.750
Squat, squat!

02:06.750 --> 02:08.458
-I'm so pumped.
-Are you sure you don't want to

02:08.458 --> 02:09.500
take up the extension?

02:09.500 --> 02:10.834
You could save
up to five percent.

02:10.834 --> 02:12.166
No, look, I appreciate it,

02:12.166 --> 02:13.417
but there's no doubt in my mind

02:13.417 --> 02:15.125
it is the ten-year
platinum package.

02:15.125 --> 02:16.625
You know, 'cause we might move.

02:16.625 --> 02:18.583
CLINTON: The ten-year plan
is a great plan,

02:18.583 --> 02:21.125
and you get two free
car washes with that.

02:21.125 --> 02:22.750
-Per month?
-No.

02:22.750 --> 02:27.583
♪

02:27.583 --> 02:29.291
JEN: Oh, you're up early.

02:29.291 --> 02:31.500
Got a new paper route
I didn't know about?

02:31.500 --> 02:34.291
GREG: Ugh, I was late
for my belly busters class

02:34.291 --> 02:35.667
because I was
spending all this time

02:35.667 --> 02:37.500
trying to get my phone
in this cool new holster,

02:37.500 --> 02:39.542
but now I can't get
the phone to work.

02:39.542 --> 02:42.709
JEN: Honey,
this has 900 calories,

02:42.709 --> 02:46.291
56 grams of sugar,
and 87 carbs.

02:46.291 --> 02:48.875
This is quite a meal
you're replacing.

02:48.875 --> 02:50.208
GREG: Oh, no,
that's a supplement.

02:50.208 --> 02:51.959
I just ate six eggs.

02:51.959 --> 02:54.166
Yeah, Clinton says I
gotta have calories to burn,

02:54.166 --> 02:56.291
otherwise I'm just gonna
burn away all my muscle.

02:56.291 --> 02:57.250
Who's Clinton?

02:57.250 --> 02:58.667
Who is Clinton?

02:58.667 --> 03:00.959
Uh, that dude right there.

03:00.959 --> 03:04.000
-He only charged me $80.
-Oh, bargain city!

03:04.000 --> 03:08.041
Um, I love your enthusiasm,
don't ever change.

03:08.041 --> 03:09.458
I just wanna make sure

03:09.458 --> 03:12.917
that you haven't lost sight
of why you're doing this.

03:12.917 --> 03:15.417
I'm doing this for Lark,

03:15.417 --> 03:17.375
so that I can be there for her.

03:17.375 --> 03:18.667
(baby crying)

03:18.667 --> 03:19.959
But can you go get her

03:19.959 --> 03:22.417
because I am running late
to my double CrossFit class?

03:22.417 --> 03:23.583
Okay, thanks.

03:23.583 --> 03:26.041
It's where we trick
each other into working out.

03:26.041 --> 03:27.750
(baby crying)

03:27.750 --> 03:28.792
Hey!

03:28.792 --> 03:31.750
♪

03:31.750 --> 03:34.625
Daddy's gonna get big!

03:34.625 --> 03:37.125
(grunting)

03:37.125 --> 03:44.041
♪

03:46.709 --> 03:49.208
(clearing throat)

03:49.208 --> 03:56.166
♪

04:06.917 --> 04:09.333
(door opening)

04:14.625 --> 04:18.542
Greg, what is this bike?

04:18.542 --> 04:21.458
What on Earth are you doing?

04:21.458 --> 04:22.875
Is that my razor?

04:22.875 --> 04:24.792
Gearin' up for my first ride.

04:24.792 --> 04:26.125
You know it's twice the cardio

04:26.125 --> 04:27.917
than on those stupid
stationary machines?

04:27.917 --> 04:29.500
Yeah, and you get
to be out in nature.

04:29.500 --> 04:30.709
I love nature!

04:30.709 --> 04:32.125
You went to the doctor

04:32.125 --> 04:35.000
because you thought
you were allergic to wind.

04:35.000 --> 04:37.709
Yeah, but he gave me a cream.

04:37.709 --> 04:39.375
Um, what happened to the gym?

04:39.375 --> 04:41.041
Oh, phew, no,
I'm done with the gym.

04:41.041 --> 04:43.375
Ten years is all those suckers
are gonna get outta me.

04:43.375 --> 04:44.709
Ten years?

04:44.709 --> 04:46.834
Did you see the baby seat
that I got for Lark?

04:46.834 --> 04:50.000
I can get my workout in
and spend time with her.

04:50.000 --> 04:52.208
I mean, that's what this
whole thing is about, you know,

04:52.208 --> 04:54.333
me spending time with Lark.

04:54.333 --> 04:55.750
(baby crying)

04:55.750 --> 04:57.125
Oh, uh, do you mind gettin' her?

04:57.125 --> 04:58.959
I can't walk on
these bike shoes.

04:58.959 --> 05:04.917
♪

05:04.917 --> 05:06.625
Okay, hey, huge deal

05:06.625 --> 05:08.667
that we are not getting
a babysitter for an overnight,

05:08.667 --> 05:11.500
so do not make me regret this.

05:11.500 --> 05:12.750
All right, Mom-Mom and Pop-Pop

05:12.750 --> 05:14.458
are right across the street
if you need anything,

05:14.458 --> 05:16.250
although don't need
anything after 8:00 PM

05:16.250 --> 05:17.709
because they will be sleeping.

05:17.709 --> 05:20.625
All right, I trust you.

05:20.625 --> 05:22.667
I trust you most of the time.

05:22.667 --> 05:24.917
I trust you, I really trust you.

05:24.917 --> 05:27.041
Really, okay, bring it in, guy.

05:27.041 --> 05:28.917
Be good, you know.

05:28.917 --> 05:31.000
Uh, number for
the hotel's on the fridge.

05:31.000 --> 05:33.625
If we don't answer right away
it's 'cause we're...

05:33.625 --> 05:35.041
getting ice,

05:35.041 --> 05:37.000
and we'll call you back
in around 15 minutes.

05:37.000 --> 05:40.208
-Oh, 15 minutes!
-Make sure we both get some ice.

05:40.208 --> 05:41.959
Hi, what's this for?

05:41.959 --> 05:43.542
Well, ice always
goes better with vodka.

05:43.542 --> 05:45.333
-Okay, gotta go, kids, bye!
-Bye-bye, love you!

05:45.333 --> 05:48.041
SAM: Bye, Mom, have fun, bye!

05:48.041 --> 05:49.333
I've got five people
comin' over.

05:49.333 --> 05:50.959
I've got my whole class,
I wanna be remembered as

05:50.959 --> 05:52.417
the guy who threw huge ragers,

05:52.417 --> 05:55.166
not just the kid who wore
a top hat in the yearbook.

05:55.166 --> 05:56.875
Just poop your pants.

05:56.875 --> 05:58.542
That stays with people.

05:58.542 --> 06:01.667
Mason S. has been
coasting on it since pre-K.

06:01.667 --> 06:04.709
♪

06:04.709 --> 06:06.458
TYLER: There's, like,
eight people here.

06:06.458 --> 06:07.834
First party with
my parents outta town,

06:07.834 --> 06:08.875
and hardly anybody shows up,

06:08.875 --> 06:11.125
I can't make
a legend outta that.

06:11.125 --> 06:13.000
It's not that bad.

06:13.000 --> 06:15.542
SOPHIA: Doin' a jigsaw
puzzle in the kitchen

06:15.542 --> 06:17.083
if anyone's interested.

06:17.083 --> 06:20.792
BOY: Oh, two bunnies
in a basket!

06:20.792 --> 06:23.917
-Really?
-Okay, it's bad.

06:23.917 --> 06:26.834
Hey, what if we play
everyone our new track?

06:26.834 --> 06:28.041
-That's genius.
-Okay, perfect,

06:28.041 --> 06:29.917
and I'm gonna tweet
all our Funeral Goose fans.

06:29.917 --> 06:32.750
Are you sure this place
can handle six more people?

06:32.750 --> 06:36.583
♪

06:36.583 --> 06:39.667
-For you, yeah!
-Thank you!

06:39.667 --> 06:42.959
♪

06:42.959 --> 06:45.917
-Cheers!
-Yup!

06:45.917 --> 06:47.875
-Mm.
-Mm!

06:47.875 --> 06:49.166
Wow, that's really smooth,

06:49.166 --> 06:51.166
-it's like water.
-Yeah!

06:51.166 --> 06:53.750
♪

06:53.750 --> 06:56.500
Is this just water,
or am I an alcoholic?

06:56.500 --> 06:58.709
♪

06:58.709 --> 07:01.750
I think somebody swapped out
our vodka for water.

07:01.750 --> 07:03.500
♪

07:03.500 --> 07:07.125
<i>♪ I know we're supposed to be</i>
<i>birds of a feather,</i>

07:07.125 --> 07:10.709
<i>fly V formation</i>
<i>so happy together ♪</i>

07:10.709 --> 07:14.750
<i>♪ But you ostracized me</i>
<i>you flew away, don't care ♪</i>

07:14.750 --> 07:17.417
<i>♪ But you come back anyway ♪</i>

07:17.417 --> 07:21.000
<i>♪ I'm trapped</i>
<i>in your love cage ♪</i>

07:21.000 --> 07:26.792
<i>♪ I'm cooped</i>
<i>in your love cage ♪</i>

07:26.792 --> 07:29.208
(cheering)

07:32.208 --> 07:33.750
Now this is a party!

07:33.750 --> 07:36.542
Tyler, got some bad news.

07:36.542 --> 07:39.583
One, your band is the worst!

07:39.583 --> 07:42.375
And two, Mom and Dad
are on their way home.

07:42.375 --> 07:44.375
What, our band is not the worst.

07:44.375 --> 07:45.750
How do you know
they're coming home?

07:45.750 --> 07:47.333
I use find your phone.

07:47.333 --> 07:48.625
They're an hour away.

07:48.625 --> 07:50.583
Um, guys, um,
thanks for coming, everyone,

07:50.583 --> 07:54.125
but Funeral Goose has to
fly south for the night, so...

07:54.125 --> 07:56.417
(people murmuring)

07:56.417 --> 07:57.875
You guys, the party's over.

07:57.875 --> 08:00.083
Yeah, spread your wings
and fly out.

08:00.083 --> 08:01.959
(people murmuring)

08:01.959 --> 08:03.041
Get out!

08:03.041 --> 08:06.041
Oh, now I get it!

08:06.041 --> 08:08.250
They're deaf.

08:08.250 --> 08:09.834
Play "Death, Death, Goose!"

08:09.834 --> 08:12.208
I drove three hours to hear
"Death, Death, Goose."

08:12.208 --> 08:13.250
Play it!

08:13.250 --> 08:14.875
-Yeah!
-No, no, no, no.

08:14.875 --> 08:16.375
(cheering)

08:19.250 --> 08:21.208
Now, what's
the symbolism of that?

08:21.208 --> 08:23.917
This expresses my need

08:23.917 --> 08:26.083
to cover up a mistake
that I made earlier.

08:26.083 --> 08:27.250
Oh.

08:27.250 --> 08:28.417
Actually, I made
a lot of mistakes.

08:28.417 --> 08:30.458
This started out as
a portrait of you.

08:30.458 --> 08:32.041
-Aw!
TYLER: Uncle Matt!

08:32.041 --> 08:34.250
-Hey!
-Hey, Uncle Matt, um,

08:34.250 --> 08:35.417
I need your help with something.

08:35.417 --> 08:36.667
-Okay.
-I need to clear out a party

08:36.667 --> 08:37.792
really fast.

08:37.792 --> 08:38.875
Did you have your band play?

08:38.875 --> 08:40.208
Yes.

08:40.208 --> 08:41.667
And they stayed?

08:41.667 --> 08:42.834
-Of course.
-Of course they stayed,

08:42.834 --> 08:44.417
-it's a good band.
COLLEEN: You know, I've

08:44.417 --> 08:45.917
cleared out a party
or two in my day.

08:45.917 --> 08:47.750
My dad's weddings were
always getting out of control.

08:47.750 --> 08:50.792
Whoa, how many times
your dad get married?

08:50.792 --> 08:52.750
How many times,
or how many different women?

08:52.750 --> 08:55.208
-Mm.
-Guys, can we go?

08:55.208 --> 08:57.208
-Oh, yeah.
-Oh, sure.

08:57.208 --> 08:59.625
(siren blaring)

08:59.625 --> 09:01.875
Everybody, cops are here,
get out now.

09:01.875 --> 09:03.250
SAM: Come on,
everybody out the back.

09:03.250 --> 09:04.208
Move, move, move,

09:04.208 --> 09:05.542
-come on, people!
TYLER: Go, go!

09:05.542 --> 09:07.000
SAM: Out the back,
come on, come on,

09:07.000 --> 09:08.417
go, go, go, go, go, go,

09:08.417 --> 09:10.709
-come on!
-Hey, that was awesome!

09:10.709 --> 09:12.041
That was so easy!

09:12.041 --> 09:13.625
We didn't even
have to tase anyone.

09:13.625 --> 09:15.458
I just had a party
busted by the cops.

09:15.458 --> 09:16.917
That's instant street cred.

09:16.917 --> 09:18.375
CLEMENTINE:
You're a huge deal now.

09:18.375 --> 09:19.625
Bigger than that
marching band kid

09:19.625 --> 09:21.208
-in the wheelchair.
-I don't know.

09:21.208 --> 09:23.291
You owe me big.

09:23.291 --> 09:26.542
I just lent you
20 bucks last week.

09:26.542 --> 09:27.959
And we're even.

09:27.959 --> 09:29.583
♪

09:29.583 --> 09:31.333
HEATHER: Oh, hello!
TYLER: Oh, hey!

09:31.333 --> 09:32.458
What are you doin' here?

09:32.458 --> 09:34.375
Oh, we just thought
maybe you guys should

09:34.375 --> 09:36.917
try a little alcohol.

09:36.917 --> 09:37.959
Drink it.

09:37.959 --> 09:39.208
No, thank you.

09:39.208 --> 09:40.750
-Come on!
-Drink it.

09:40.750 --> 09:42.875
No!

09:42.875 --> 09:44.083
Sophia, you drink it.

09:44.083 --> 09:45.166
TYLER: Dad, what are you doing?
HEATHER: Come on,

09:45.166 --> 09:47.000
drink your drink.

09:47.000 --> 09:48.458
There you go!

09:48.458 --> 09:50.500
-Oh!
-Awesome.

09:50.500 --> 09:53.875
HEATHER: That's my girl.

09:53.875 --> 09:54.834
Tastes like water.

09:54.834 --> 09:55.834
That's because it is water,

09:55.834 --> 09:58.000
now which one of you
replaced it?

09:58.000 --> 09:59.417
TYLER: Hey, I don't
even like vodka.

09:59.417 --> 10:01.291
I mean, vodka,
which one is that?

10:01.291 --> 10:03.166
Clementine, was this you?

10:03.166 --> 10:04.208
-What?
-Well, you don't have

10:04.208 --> 10:05.375
to answer that, Clemmy.

10:05.375 --> 10:08.625
She would never do
something like that!

10:08.625 --> 10:10.583
-Then, who did it?
<i>REPORTER: A government bill</i>

10:10.583 --> 10:14.000
<i>-to crack down on--</i>
-You wanted vodka tonic.

10:14.000 --> 10:15.709
But I thought
we were out of vodka?

10:15.709 --> 10:17.125
We were.

10:17.125 --> 10:18.792
Now Tim and Heather are.

10:18.792 --> 10:21.291
(laughing)

10:21.291 --> 10:22.500
♪

10:22.500 --> 10:23.709
-Cheers!
-Cheers!

10:23.709 --> 10:27.417
♪

10:27.417 --> 10:30.041
HEATHER: I couldn't by chance
interest you in a purse

10:30.041 --> 10:32.375
with my hand-sewn face
from ninth grade on it?

10:32.375 --> 10:34.083
Yes, you could.

10:34.083 --> 10:35.625
-I'm a hoarder.
-Oh!

10:38.083 --> 10:40.333
♪

10:40.333 --> 10:42.500
TIM: Here's our donation.

10:42.500 --> 10:47.417
Hope people like half-built Lego
sets and Blackberry chargers.

10:47.417 --> 10:49.125
-Where's your box?
-I got nothin' to sell

10:49.125 --> 10:51.625
but the shirt on my back, man.

10:51.625 --> 10:53.500
Nice shirt.

10:53.500 --> 10:54.750
Twenty bucks.

10:54.750 --> 10:58.625
Sold!

10:58.625 --> 11:00.625
(chuckling)

11:00.625 --> 11:03.875
Yeah, I used to have one
just like this.

11:03.875 --> 11:06.875
Heather gave it away.

11:06.875 --> 11:09.875
♪

11:09.875 --> 11:11.458
Oh, wow.

11:11.458 --> 11:12.875
♪

11:12.875 --> 11:14.542
HEATHER: They can't all
be important to you.

11:14.542 --> 11:17.083
This entire group
is in stuffed animal jail.

11:17.083 --> 11:19.625
Yeah, 'cause one is a liar!

11:19.625 --> 11:21.417
And until it confesses,

11:21.417 --> 11:23.917
Unicorn,

11:23.917 --> 11:25.917
they're all staying in there.

11:25.917 --> 11:27.667
Okay, well,
whatever you can fit

11:27.667 --> 11:29.208
in this bin, you get to keep.

11:29.208 --> 11:32.250
Everything else
goes into the yard sale.

11:32.250 --> 11:34.583
Why don't I just throw out
all your children?

11:34.583 --> 11:36.834
♪

11:36.834 --> 11:38.458
GREG: Look, she likes to get
gifts for everybody.

11:38.458 --> 11:39.667
That's kind of her thing.

11:39.667 --> 11:41.667
I know, and it's
very sweet of your mom,

11:41.667 --> 11:45.750
it's just I don't really
like antique opium pipes,

11:45.750 --> 11:48.208
even if I do look like
one of those fun women

11:48.208 --> 11:49.625
who would have
done that back then.

11:49.625 --> 11:51.041
HEATHER: Oh, you got
one of those too?

11:51.041 --> 11:52.083
-Her discovering eBay...
JEN: Yeah.

11:52.083 --> 11:53.792
...was the beginning of the end.

11:53.792 --> 11:58.583
I have the exact same
pile of stuff collecting dust.

11:58.583 --> 12:00.333
JEN: I mean, what is
the statute of limitations

12:00.333 --> 12:02.041
on humoring somebody?

12:02.041 --> 12:04.041
No, you're right,
the longer we wait,

12:04.041 --> 12:05.583
the more guilty
we're gonna feel.

12:05.583 --> 12:08.917
JEN: Yeah, and I'm gonna
go out on a limb here and say

12:08.917 --> 12:13.083
if you haven't used this
Victorian nursing kit yet,

12:13.083 --> 12:14.709
ya might not ever.

12:14.709 --> 12:18.625
But you can't sell this stuff
at her garage sale,

12:18.625 --> 12:20.375
all right, it's gonna
hurt her feelings.

12:20.375 --> 12:22.709
No, Greg is right,
Greg is right.

12:22.709 --> 12:25.959
We have to sell it
secretly over here.

12:25.959 --> 12:28.792
Oh, I like that.

12:28.792 --> 12:30.709
-Good idea, Greg.
-That's not what I said.

12:30.709 --> 12:32.041
Almost verbatim.

12:32.041 --> 12:34.750
♪

12:34.750 --> 12:36.542
JOHN: Oh, nothin' like
a well-made shoe.

12:36.542 --> 12:39.041
-Fifty cents.
-Deal!

12:39.041 --> 12:40.583
And the right one's ten bucks.

12:40.583 --> 12:43.208
Oh, I don't need it,
my husband's an amputee.

12:43.208 --> 12:45.458
Oh, no, no, I meant
the right one's fifty cents,

12:45.458 --> 12:48.375
and the left one's ten bucks.

12:48.375 --> 12:50.792
I see you eyeing
the baking tins there.

12:50.792 --> 12:53.542
I couldn't by chance
interest you in a purse

12:53.542 --> 12:55.834
with my hand-sewn face
from ninth grade on it?

12:55.834 --> 12:57.625
Yes, you could!

12:57.625 --> 12:59.709
-I'm a hoarder.
-Oh!

12:59.709 --> 13:01.458
Oh, well come here.

13:01.458 --> 13:03.458
-I shouldn't be here.
-Oh, don't listen to that voice.

13:03.458 --> 13:05.166
Why don't you come with me
across the street?

13:05.166 --> 13:06.625
♪

13:06.625 --> 13:07.834
Oh, you takin' those?

13:07.834 --> 13:10.125
Thank you, come back soon.

13:10.125 --> 13:12.542
Hey, are you feeling
a little guilty about this?

13:12.542 --> 13:14.166
No, no, no, no, no.

13:14.166 --> 13:17.417
This stuff is gonna be
with people who want it.

13:17.417 --> 13:19.667
(phone ringing)

13:19.667 --> 13:21.250
Uh, hi, Mom, hi!

13:21.250 --> 13:22.834
<i>JOAN: Honey, where are you?</i>

13:22.834 --> 13:26.041
<i>I need a price, hon,</i>
<i>on Tyler's football pads.</i>

13:26.041 --> 13:28.959
Oh, you know what,
I am helping this woman

13:28.959 --> 13:31.166
load Dad's encyclopedias
into her car.

13:31.166 --> 13:32.291
I'll be right there.

13:32.291 --> 13:34.041
♪

13:34.041 --> 13:35.125
MAN: Oh, yeah.

13:35.125 --> 13:36.834
Well, you are
like a professional

13:36.834 --> 13:38.417
yard sale shopper, huh?

13:38.417 --> 13:40.125
Look at that thing,
that is so cool.

13:40.125 --> 13:41.458
You like that bad boy, huh?

13:41.458 --> 13:43.458
-Yeah.
-I paid 100 bucks for that.

13:43.458 --> 13:46.083
Gonna try to fix it up
and get $250 out of it.

13:46.083 --> 13:48.583
-250 bucks?
-Yeah.

13:48.583 --> 13:50.417
-Sold!
-What?

13:50.417 --> 13:51.917
Yeah!

13:51.917 --> 13:54.500
Yeah?

13:54.500 --> 13:56.083
JEN: You know what,
come with me across the street,

13:56.083 --> 13:57.834
we've got some good stuff
I wanted to show you.

13:57.834 --> 13:59.250
Where are you going?

13:59.250 --> 14:01.291
Hm, oh, um,

14:01.291 --> 14:04.667
uh, this is, uh, my friend
Shannon from high school.

14:04.667 --> 14:06.500
What, I just met you.

14:06.500 --> 14:08.500
I'm not Shannon.

14:08.500 --> 14:11.291
Shannon, you've always been
such a lyin' bitch.

14:11.291 --> 14:13.208
-Who you callin' a bitch?
-Okay, you know what,

14:13.208 --> 14:14.834
let's go look at that
high school yearbook,

14:14.834 --> 14:19.250
Miss Most Likely to Play Along
in a Hypothetical Situation.

14:19.250 --> 14:20.291
WOMAN: You better
have something good

14:20.291 --> 14:22.625
-over here.
-I've got gold over here.

14:22.625 --> 14:24.417
JOHN: Heather,
you got any change?

14:24.417 --> 14:26.417
We're, uh...

14:26.417 --> 14:28.542
Whoa, what are you doin'?

14:28.542 --> 14:30.583
I'm selling all the stuff that
Mom gave me that I don't like,

14:30.583 --> 14:31.667
please don't tell her.

14:31.667 --> 14:32.875
Tell her?

14:32.875 --> 14:36.208
I'm gonna go grab
a box of crap that she gave me.

14:38.125 --> 14:40.542
(tuning guitar)

14:42.792 --> 14:44.291
Honey?

14:44.291 --> 14:46.667
Jen just took someone
from the yard sale

14:46.667 --> 14:48.291
over to Heather's house.

14:48.291 --> 14:50.834
I was wondering if you knew
what was going on?

14:50.834 --> 14:52.583
I do not.

14:52.583 --> 14:54.917
You're lying to me!

14:54.917 --> 14:56.750
-Nope.
-Why are you lying to me?

14:56.750 --> 15:00.333
I'm gonna go, uh, price out
some of these, uh,

15:00.333 --> 15:03.083
-things.
-That's also a lie!

15:03.083 --> 15:04.291
Why?

15:04.291 --> 15:06.542
Why are you lying to me?

15:06.542 --> 15:08.166
Where are you going?

15:08.166 --> 15:09.291
Greg!

15:09.291 --> 15:11.458
She's onto us!

15:11.458 --> 15:13.291
Oh, no, oh no,
she's onto us.

15:13.291 --> 15:15.125
She's onto us, shut it down!

15:15.125 --> 15:16.875
(garage door closing)

15:16.875 --> 15:18.375
WOMAN: What's going on?
HEATHER: Some of this stuff

15:18.375 --> 15:20.333
is glow in the dark,
so we're doin' this for effect.

15:20.333 --> 15:22.125
Yeah, works great
in a dorm room.

15:25.500 --> 15:26.583
-Hi!
HEATHER: Hi!

15:26.583 --> 15:28.542
Hi!

15:28.542 --> 15:30.041
Oh.

15:30.041 --> 15:32.792
Um, we were just, uh...

15:32.792 --> 15:34.458
-Cataloging.
-...organizing.

15:34.458 --> 15:37.417
Oh, look, I gave you
this for your first

15:37.417 --> 15:39.583
-wedding anniversary.
-Yeah!

15:39.583 --> 15:41.250
Oh, my gosh!

15:41.250 --> 15:43.000
And I got you this when you

15:43.000 --> 15:46.083
-passed the bar!
-Bar, and I love it.

15:46.083 --> 15:49.250
This is stuff that I...

15:49.250 --> 15:51.333
gave you,

15:51.333 --> 15:53.166
so what's happening?

15:53.166 --> 15:55.166
Okay, we're...

15:55.166 --> 15:57.875
selling it, and we didn't
wanna hurt your feelings.

15:57.875 --> 16:01.000
JEN: And it really is
all so beautiful.

16:01.000 --> 16:02.917
You have wonderful taste

16:02.917 --> 16:05.291
-in, um, East Asian--
-No more, no more, I understand.

16:05.291 --> 16:07.000
I understand, I understand.

16:07.000 --> 16:08.583
In the future,

16:08.583 --> 16:11.125
if I give you something
and you don't like it,

16:11.125 --> 16:12.750
just tell me.

16:12.750 --> 16:14.917
HEATHER: Really?
-Of course, just tell me,

16:14.917 --> 16:17.792
and then I'll just take it back.

16:17.792 --> 16:18.834
That's all.

16:18.834 --> 16:20.208
See you later.

16:20.208 --> 16:22.750
♪

16:22.750 --> 16:23.750
What just happened?

16:23.750 --> 16:25.625
♪

16:25.625 --> 16:27.000
She took it back.

16:27.000 --> 16:28.500
JOAN: Woo, this is heavy!

16:28.500 --> 16:31.500
Okay, well, at least we
got rid of a bunch of junk.

16:31.500 --> 16:32.542
-Right, yup.
TIM: Hey, Heather,

16:32.542 --> 16:33.792
look what I bought!

16:33.792 --> 16:34.959
Startin' a man cave.

16:34.959 --> 16:39.583
♪

16:39.583 --> 16:40.875
He got out, he got away.

16:40.875 --> 16:42.041
Why are you looking up?

16:42.041 --> 16:43.667
Well, underestimating
the lobster

16:43.667 --> 16:44.750
was our first mistake.

16:46.959 --> 16:49.417
♪

16:49.417 --> 16:50.625
TIM: Look at this, you guys!

16:50.625 --> 16:52.583
My brother sent me a lobster!

16:52.583 --> 16:54.125
(cheering)

16:54.125 --> 16:56.041
This little guy

16:56.041 --> 16:57.625
came all the way from Maine,

16:57.625 --> 16:59.500
which is where
I went to college.

16:59.500 --> 17:02.750
These things are like
the state bird up there.

17:02.750 --> 17:04.208
Even after that long flight,

17:04.208 --> 17:05.917
he's still got
a lot of fight in him.

17:05.917 --> 17:07.917
I respect that in a lobster.

17:07.917 --> 17:09.208
SOPHIA: I think he's cute.

17:09.208 --> 17:10.625
I'm gonna name him Billy

17:10.625 --> 17:13.875
after that kid at school who
was rescued from a tool shed.

17:13.875 --> 17:16.250
Maybe it's not such
a great idea to name him.

17:16.250 --> 17:19.792
You know why, because they're
going to boil him alive.

17:19.792 --> 17:21.166
Samantha's right.

17:21.166 --> 17:22.375
Maybe we shouldn't
boil him alive.

17:22.375 --> 17:24.291
-Thank you.
-We should just bash his head in

17:24.291 --> 17:26.333
with a hammer first, someone
hand me that meat mallet.

17:26.333 --> 17:28.208
-What?
-Oh, he heard me.

17:28.208 --> 17:31.333
This is barbaric,
I'm out of here!

17:31.333 --> 17:35.291
JOAN: Oh, I understand people
have problems killing animals

17:35.291 --> 17:38.041
because there's so many
other things for us to eat.

17:38.041 --> 17:40.583
SOPHIA: So, you have
a problem with it, Mom-Mom?

17:40.583 --> 17:43.041
Oh, no, lobsters are delicious.

17:43.041 --> 17:50.000
♪

17:52.792 --> 17:55.208
Billy, Billy?

17:55.208 --> 17:56.583
He got out, he got away.

17:56.583 --> 17:57.709
Why are you looking up?

17:57.709 --> 17:59.417
Well, underestimating
the lobster

17:59.417 --> 18:01.417
-was our first mistake.
-No, honey,

18:01.417 --> 18:02.709
I don't think it was.

18:02.709 --> 18:06.917
I think that someone
probably took him.

18:06.917 --> 18:09.208
Someone took him,
that's awesome.

18:09.208 --> 18:12.458
♪

18:12.458 --> 18:15.041
I have a girlfriend
for the first time in my life.

18:15.041 --> 18:16.208
If I'm gonna steal
something from you,

18:16.208 --> 18:17.667
it's not gonna be a lobster.

18:17.667 --> 18:19.417
♪

18:19.417 --> 18:21.333
I don't know!

18:21.333 --> 18:23.000
But if you find Billy,

18:23.000 --> 18:26.375
tell him Imogene was hoping
to have a drink with him,

18:26.375 --> 18:27.917
see where the night took them.

18:27.917 --> 18:29.625
♪

18:29.625 --> 18:32.875
So, we are officially
out of suspects.

18:32.875 --> 18:34.750
Are we?

18:34.750 --> 18:36.917
I've been with you
the entire time.

18:36.917 --> 18:38.041
You're right, I'm sorry.

18:38.041 --> 18:41.625
I'm just, I'm really hungry...

18:41.625 --> 18:43.959
for the truth.

18:43.959 --> 18:48.208
Mom, you didn't by chance happen
to take Billy, did you?

18:48.208 --> 18:51.458
No, of course
I didn't take Billy!

18:51.458 --> 18:53.875
Never, but I know who did.

18:53.875 --> 18:56.166
Well, somebody knows something.

18:56.166 --> 18:58.291
Well, I just told you I know.

18:58.291 --> 18:59.458
Mm-hmm.

18:59.458 --> 19:01.000
Yeah, I'll get it outta ya.

19:01.000 --> 19:02.083
♪

19:04.291 --> 19:06.125
♪

19:06.125 --> 19:08.125
Hey, Dad, where ya goin'?

19:08.125 --> 19:09.375
-Who, me?
-Yeah.

19:09.375 --> 19:12.083
I was just goin'
for a Sunday drive.

19:12.083 --> 19:14.458
Oh, okay because it's Saturday.

19:14.458 --> 19:16.417
Yeah, where's the lobster?

19:16.417 --> 19:17.667
He has a name.

19:17.667 --> 19:19.750
I mean, how would I know?

19:19.750 --> 19:21.875
JOAN: John...

19:21.875 --> 19:23.625
tell them.

19:23.625 --> 19:25.375
Okay, I took him.

19:25.375 --> 19:27.834
I looked it up,
and lobsters this size

19:27.834 --> 19:29.291
are like 40 years old.

19:29.291 --> 19:31.625
And I don't know how many
that is in human years,

19:31.625 --> 19:33.834
but it's at least 40.

19:33.834 --> 19:36.750
Now, he's traveled all over
the world, kinda like me,

19:36.750 --> 19:40.500
and he deserves a better
ending than Tim's toilet.

19:40.500 --> 19:43.208
Can't argue with that.

19:43.208 --> 19:44.750
Where is he, Dad?

19:47.333 --> 19:49.959
Oh, oh.

19:49.959 --> 19:52.417
I'm gonna release him
back into the sea.

19:52.417 --> 19:53.959
He's starting to look

19:53.959 --> 19:56.250
like E.T. in that ravine.

19:56.250 --> 19:58.583
If we don't get him
back in the water,

19:58.583 --> 20:00.583
I'm gonna lose my strength too.

20:00.583 --> 20:01.875
♪

20:01.875 --> 20:03.834
Well, carry on, soldier.

20:03.834 --> 20:05.875
You're gonna have a lot
of great stories to tell

20:05.875 --> 20:07.750
when you get back to Maine.

20:07.750 --> 20:11.750
♪

20:11.750 --> 20:13.583
SAM: Bye, Billy!
HEATHER: Bye, Billy!

20:13.583 --> 20:16.166
JOAN: Safe home, Billy!
JOHN: Bye, Bill.

20:16.166 --> 20:17.333
JOAN: Honey,

20:17.333 --> 20:19.083
you remembered to
take the rubber bands

20:19.083 --> 20:21.750
off the claws, right?

20:21.750 --> 20:24.333
-Uh...
-The rubber bands off his claws?

20:24.333 --> 20:26.375
-Well, yeah, yeah.
-Okay.

20:26.375 --> 20:28.458
(waves crashing)

20:28.458 --> 20:31.041
Uh...

20:31.041 --> 20:35.000
I'm gonna just
take a quick swim.

20:35.000 --> 20:36.166
I'll be right back.

20:36.166 --> 20:43.083
♪

21:05.166 --> 21:08.125
♪
